01:12:17.390 --> 01:12:21.050
for this wave in the
presence of a potential.

01:12:24.800 --> 01:12:25.370
OK.

01:12:25.370 --> 01:12:30.170
There are cases in which the
quantum mechanical nature

01:12:30.170 --> 01:12:34.280
of the nuclei actually
becomes relevant.

01:12:34.280 --> 01:12:38.750
There is much less
modeling activity on that

01:12:38.750 --> 01:12:43.100
because it's just fairly
computationally expensive.

01:12:43.100 --> 01:12:46.010
One of the cases in
which it's important

01:12:46.010 --> 01:12:49.550
is when you have a
very light nuclei.

01:12:49.550 --> 01:12:52.670
So if you have a system
that has a lot of hydrogen,

01:12:52.670 --> 01:12:56.030
well, it actually
might become relevant.

01:12:56.030 --> 01:12:59.720
And the fact that your proton
has its own wavelength,

01:12:59.720 --> 01:13:02.300
has its own delocalization,
could actually

01:13:02.300 --> 01:13:03.980
become important.

01:13:03.980 --> 01:13:08.330
And it's never going
to change dramatically

01:13:08.330 --> 01:13:10.520
the physics of the
chemistry of your system,

01:13:10.520 --> 01:13:13.160
but it's going to
introduce relevant effects.

01:13:13.160 --> 01:13:15.980
And you know, this
is actually coming

01:13:15.980 --> 01:13:20.420
from a Nature paper from 1999, a
very, very expensive simulation

01:13:20.420 --> 01:13:23.130
in which both the electronics
degrees of freedom

01:13:23.130 --> 01:13:23.990
were studied.

01:13:23.990 --> 01:13:27.650
And also, the quantum
delocalization effects

01:13:27.650 --> 01:13:30.470
on the proton were
studied, basically,

01:13:30.470 --> 01:13:34.050
for what is called a
hydrated proton in water.

01:13:34.050 --> 01:13:37.550
So if you have water and
you add a proton, well,

01:13:37.550 --> 01:13:43.160
the first thing that will
form is a hydronium ion, H3O+.

01:13:43.160 --> 01:13:46.130
And for 20, 30 years,
people had actually

01:13:46.130 --> 01:13:51.650
discussed what was the general
coordination of this proton.

01:13:51.650 --> 01:13:55.490
There was sort of a hypothesis
in which people were discussing

01:13:55.490 --> 01:13:58.340
about an Eigen
compound, from Eigen,

01:13:58.340 --> 01:14:00.200
the person that
first suggested it,

01:14:00.200 --> 01:14:05.210
a proton bound to two water
molecules basically creating

01:14:05.210 --> 01:14:09.140
an H5O 2+ system.

01:14:09.140 --> 01:14:11.990
And then there was the Zundel
hypothesis in which this

01:14:11.990 --> 01:14:16.790
hydronium ion, H3O+, was
surrounded by three water

01:14:16.790 --> 01:14:17.930
molecules.

01:14:17.930 --> 01:14:20.450
And you know-- nothing
better than doing an accurate

01:14:20.450 --> 01:14:22.670
simulation to find it out.

01:14:22.670 --> 01:14:26.060
And being finally a quantum
mechanical simulation,

01:14:26.060 --> 01:14:28.190
the result was
that it's actually

01:14:28.190 --> 01:14:31.280
the proton is in what is
called a functional state.

01:14:31.280 --> 01:14:35.780
Sort of it stays half of the
time in an Eigen state, that

01:14:35.780 --> 01:14:39.110
is a state predicted
by Eigen, and half

01:14:39.110 --> 01:14:41.000
of the time in a Zundel state.

01:14:41.000 --> 01:14:42.710
And you see this is
actually interesting,

01:14:42.710 --> 01:14:46.160
sort of comparing the
quantum mechanical prediction

01:14:46.160 --> 01:14:48.110
and the classical prediction.

01:14:48.110 --> 01:14:51.980
That is for a classical proton
in a quantum mechanical field

01:14:51.980 --> 01:14:52.880
of electrons.

01:14:52.880 --> 01:14:55.760
And you see the sort
of average position

01:14:55.760 --> 01:14:57.890
in the proton
between two molecules

01:14:57.890 --> 01:15:01.760
are sort of more
delocalized, more spread out,

01:15:01.760 --> 01:15:03.940
than in the classical case.

01:15:03.940 --> 01:15:07.250
So that is, I think,
the structure of water

01:15:07.250 --> 01:15:09.150
is interesting.

01:15:09.150 --> 01:15:11.810
There are sort of
other cases in which

01:15:11.810 --> 01:15:17.990
you have a very shallow energy
barrier between two states

01:15:17.990 --> 01:15:21.770
in which the quantum
delocalization and the quantum

01:15:21.770 --> 01:15:24.170
tunneling could be important.

01:15:24.170 --> 01:15:27.750
And something like that happened
actually in strontium titanite.

01:15:27.750 --> 01:15:33.110
That is a perovskite very
similar to the lead titanite

01:15:33.110 --> 01:15:35.480
that we have seen
in the first slide.

01:15:35.480 --> 01:15:39.590
And we remember there were
two phases, a cubic phase

01:15:39.590 --> 01:15:42.380
and a distorted
ferroelectric phase.

01:15:42.380 --> 01:15:45.710
Well, it turns out that in the
case of strontium titanite,

01:15:45.710 --> 01:15:48.350
the energy barrier
between those two phases

01:15:48.350 --> 01:15:52.130
is so shallow that
all the ions actually

01:15:52.130 --> 01:15:56.840
tunnel back and forth between
all the possible structure.

01:15:56.840 --> 01:16:00.080
And so a system that
would be ferroelectric

01:16:00.080 --> 01:16:04.100
in a classical simulation of
the ions, when we actually

01:16:04.100 --> 01:16:08.690
introduce a quantum mechanical
effect for the nucleus as well,

01:16:08.690 --> 01:16:11.240
it turns out to be the
state that keeps tunneling

01:16:11.240 --> 01:16:13.230
between all the possibilities.

01:16:13.230 --> 01:16:17.030
And so it doesn't
display ferroelectricity.

01:16:17.030 --> 01:16:19.670
The last case that is
probably the most relevant--

01:16:19.670 --> 01:16:21.240
and we'll see that
in more detail,

01:16:21.240 --> 01:16:22.760
so I haven't presented here--

01:16:22.760 --> 01:16:25.370
in which we really need
to take into account

01:16:25.370 --> 01:16:28.460
the quantum mechanical
nature of the ions

01:16:28.460 --> 01:16:31.790
has to do with
structural excitation.

01:16:31.790 --> 01:16:35.240
When you put temperature, say,
in something like a solid,

01:16:35.240 --> 01:16:40.910
you don't excite vibrational
states in a continuum way.

01:16:40.910 --> 01:16:45.380
But you actually excite
discrete vibrational states

01:16:45.380 --> 01:16:46.610
of your system.

01:16:46.610 --> 01:16:49.520
And this is sort of
fundamental to understand

01:16:49.520 --> 01:16:54.260
many thermodynamical properties
of solid, of molecules,

01:16:54.260 --> 01:16:57.320
something like the
specific heat of a solid.

01:16:57.320 --> 01:17:01.010
But we'll see examples
of that later on.

01:17:01.010 --> 01:17:04.100
And those are cases
in which we actually

01:17:04.100 --> 01:17:07.640
know very well on how to deal
with this specific problem

01:17:07.640 --> 01:17:11.810
of the quantization of
the vibrational excitation

01:17:11.810 --> 01:17:14.090
of your system.

01:17:14.090 --> 01:17:14.690
OK.

01:17:14.690 --> 01:17:17.840
So with all of this, the
first thing to remember

01:17:17.840 --> 01:17:23.400
is that electrons
actually behave as waves.

01:17:23.400 --> 01:17:26.390
So in reality, what
is quantum mechanics?

01:17:26.390 --> 01:17:29.180
It's nothing else
than the mechanics

01:17:29.180 --> 01:17:30.980
of electrons as waves.

01:17:30.980 --> 01:17:33.020
So we don't consider
it a mechanics

01:17:33.020 --> 01:17:35.900
of classical particle,
but it's the mechanics

01:17:35.900 --> 01:17:38.330
of wave-like objects.

01:17:38.330 --> 01:17:41.960
And there are going to be very
specific laws if you want them.

01:17:41.960 --> 01:17:44.330
There's going to be the
Schrodinger equation that

01:17:44.330 --> 01:17:48.330
is the Newton equivalent
of the equation of motion.

01:17:48.330 --> 01:17:49.820
But there are also
going to be very

01:17:49.820 --> 01:17:52.850
specific computational
constraints

01:17:52.850 --> 01:17:54.920
on how we describe a wave.

01:17:54.920 --> 01:17:55.610
OK.

01:17:55.610 --> 01:17:57.050
What you are very
familiar is sort

01:17:57.050 --> 01:17:58.570
of the mechanics of a particle.

01:17:58.570 --> 01:18:00.110
So in the mechanics
of a particle,

01:18:00.110 --> 01:18:02.150
you have Newton
equation of motion.

01:18:02.150 --> 01:18:05.570
You have mass times acceleration
is equal to the force.

01:18:05.570 --> 01:18:08.720
That's an ordinary second-order
differential equation.

01:18:08.720 --> 01:18:11.900
That basically
means that what you

01:18:11.900 --> 01:18:16.490
are going to obtain
by integrating

01:18:16.490 --> 01:18:19.010
this equation of
motion is actually

01:18:19.010 --> 01:18:21.860
the trajectory as
a function of time

01:18:21.860 --> 01:18:24.290
and the first derivative
that is the velocity.

01:18:24.290 --> 01:18:28.430
And because its second-order
differential equation,

01:18:28.430 --> 01:18:30.800
what you really need
to define that is, say,

01:18:30.800 --> 01:18:32.480
something like the
initial condition.

01:18:32.480 --> 01:18:35.030
You need to define
where your particle is

01:18:35.030 --> 01:18:38.360
at a certain instant and
what is its velocity.

01:18:38.360 --> 01:18:40.820
And once you know that
and you know, say,

01:18:40.820 --> 01:18:45.380
what is the force, something
like the gravitational force

01:18:45.380 --> 01:18:50.040
in this case, well, you are able
to integrate your trajectory.

01:18:50.040 --> 01:18:50.630
OK.

01:18:50.630 --> 01:18:53.760
So this is sort of integration
of the equation of motion.

01:18:53.760 --> 01:18:58.550
But what is really important
is that your dynamical system

01:18:58.550 --> 01:19:03.600
that is your particle moving
around is perfectly described.

01:19:03.600 --> 01:19:06.530
So we know everything
about that particle.

01:19:06.530 --> 01:19:11.180
If I have every instant in
time, I give you two vectors,

01:19:11.180 --> 01:19:11.720
basically.

01:19:11.720 --> 01:19:15.530
I give the position,
and I give the velocity.

01:19:15.530 --> 01:19:20.160
And in a sort of three
dimension, that's six numbers.

01:19:20.160 --> 01:19:20.750
OK.

01:19:20.750 --> 01:19:22.310
So it's very easy to remember.

01:19:22.310 --> 01:19:25.340
And it's very easy to
store in a computer.

01:19:25.340 --> 01:19:28.490
And this is my last
slide for today.

01:19:28.490 --> 01:19:32.750
The amazing
computational complexity

01:19:32.750 --> 01:19:37.190
that we have when we actually
need to describe a wave

01:19:37.190 --> 01:19:40.920
is that to describe a
wave that is basically

01:19:40.920 --> 01:19:47.240
a delocalized excitation a
wave is an amplitude everywhere

01:19:47.240 --> 01:19:48.390
in space.

01:19:48.390 --> 01:19:53.630
So even to describe a single
electron, what we need to say

01:19:53.630 --> 01:19:59.240
is that at every instant what
is the amplitude of that wave

01:19:59.240 --> 01:20:01.890
everywhere in space.

01:20:01.890 --> 01:20:05.570
And so you see we have gone
from a classical particle that

01:20:05.570 --> 01:20:09.050
was basically six
numbers at every instant

01:20:09.050 --> 01:20:13.490
to a quantum mechanical
particle that at every instant,

01:20:13.490 --> 01:20:18.150
in principle, requires a field
that covers all the space.

01:20:18.150 --> 01:20:22.970
So we need to specify the
amplitude everywhere in space.

01:20:22.970 --> 01:20:26.960
And this becomes worse
and worse as the number

01:20:26.960 --> 01:20:29.810
of particle increases.

01:20:29.810 --> 01:20:32.270
Suppose that we
had two electrons.

01:20:32.270 --> 01:20:34.580
Well, what we need
to give is now

01:20:34.580 --> 01:20:38.030
an amplitude at a
certain instant of time

01:20:38.030 --> 01:20:44.120
that would be a function of one
vector r and another vector r2.

01:20:44.120 --> 01:20:48.110
So if, by any chance,
you were satisfied

01:20:48.110 --> 01:20:52.700
by sort of describing this
in a discretized form--

01:20:52.700 --> 01:20:56.180
you see sort of discretizing
space and giving the amplitude

01:20:56.180 --> 01:20:57.620
at every point in space.

01:20:57.620 --> 01:20:59.990
And say to describe
an electron, you

01:20:59.990 --> 01:21:04.310
could be happy by just
giving, say, a million points.

01:21:04.310 --> 01:21:07.110
Well, if you want to
describe two electrons,

01:21:07.110 --> 01:21:09.860
you have to give 1 million
times 1 million points.

01:21:09.860 --> 01:21:12.380
And three electrons--
1 million to the cube

01:21:12.380 --> 01:21:13.980
and so on and so forth.

01:21:13.980 --> 01:21:17.630
So just the computational
complexity of this object

01:21:17.630 --> 01:21:18.860
explodes.

01:21:18.860 --> 01:21:22.340
That is ultimately
why it is so difficult

01:21:22.340 --> 01:21:26.960
to solve the equivalent of the
Newton's equation of motion

01:21:26.960 --> 01:21:30.420
for a quantum particle that
is the Schrodinger equation.

01:21:30.420 --> 01:21:33.680
And so with this, I'll conclude
that, if you need any reading

01:21:33.680 --> 01:21:35.690
on sort of fundamental
quantum mechanics,

01:21:35.690 --> 01:21:37.280
I can give you a suggestion.

01:21:37.280 --> 01:21:40.220
In general, sort of
physical chemistry textbooks

01:21:40.220 --> 01:21:41.600
do a very good job.

01:21:41.600 --> 01:21:43.280
There is a quantum
mechanical book

01:21:43.280 --> 01:21:45.950
that is called the Bransden
and Joachain Quantum

01:21:45.950 --> 01:21:48.110
Mechanics that is very good.

01:21:48.110 --> 01:21:50.870
But what you need
for this class you'll

01:21:50.870 --> 01:21:52.880
sort of see in the
next few slides

01:21:52.880 --> 01:21:54.950
and in the beginning
of next lecture.

01:21:54.950 --> 01:21:57.710
And then really we'll
sort of start describing

01:21:57.710 --> 01:21:59.140
electronic structure methods.

01:21:59.140 --> 01:22:01.880
That is, how do we deal
with this complexity?

01:22:01.880 --> 01:22:04.830
And how do we apply it
